text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Expansion: Hong Kong English / Chinglish exhibits a similar pattern in the way verbs are used in Indian English%0a:Author: Mingkang_L%0a:Original: [[Articles.GivingAnExamInIndianEnglish|GivingAnExamInIndianEnglish]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.Mihir_D|Mihir_D]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 17.04.2021 - 07:05%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210421-175532-462920#%0a* [-21.04.2021 - 10:55-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210421-175532-462920#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe way verbs are used in Hong Kong English / English spoken in other parts of China is quite similar to the case of Indian English.  It also exhibits direct, literal translation from Chinese to English.%0a%0aWhile in standard English, people say "turn on / off" a light. Hong Kong English / Chinglish also has “open / close” a light. This translate to the phrase 开(open)/关 (close) 灯 (light) in Simplified Chinese, or  開(open) /關(close) 燈 (light) in Traditional Chinese, which is very similar to the case in Hindi.%0a%0aWhile in standard English we say “read a book”, “watch a movie,” and “look at that bird,” the word “look” can replace the verb of all three expressions in Chinglish. This is also likely a result of direct, literal translation from Chinese to English, as in “看(look) 电影(film)” “看(look)书(book)” “看(look)那(that)只(counter, referring to a small, animate object) 鸟(bird)”%0a%0aAn example of a non-verb being literally translated in Chinese is “add oil”, which is an expression used as an encouragement and support to a person, literally 加(add) 油(oil). This expression has been been recognized by more and more people by speakers of standard English. A more well-known example is “long time no see,” which corresponds to the Chinese expression “好久(long time) 不(no) 见(look/see) “ in Mandarin or “好耐(long time) 冇 (no)見 (see)” in Cantonese. The expression “lose face” is directly transliterated from 丢(lose/throw away) 脸(face) to mean suffering a loss of respect. Despite these differences, English spoken in Hong Kong is highly intelligible to listeners from elsewhere, so there’s not much of a barrier to understanding, just like the case of Indian English.%0a%0aSource:Pang, T. (2003). Hong Kong English: A stillborn variety? English Today, 19(2), 12-18. doi:10.1017/S0266078403002037%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
