re people by speakers of standard English. A more well-known example is “long time no see,” which corresponds to the Chinese expression “好久(long time) 不(no) 见(look/see) “ in Mandarin or “好耐(long time) 冇 (no)見 (see)” in Cantonese. The expression “lose face” is directly transliterated from 丢(lose/throw away) 脸(face) to mean suffering a loss of respect. Despite these differences, English spoken in Hong Kong is highly intelligible to listeners from elsewhere, so there’s not much of a barrier to understanding, just like the case of Indian English.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source:Pang, T. (2003). Hong Kong English: A stillborn variety? English Today, 19(2), 12-18. doi:10.1017/S0266078403002037%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
